SIMPLE: rhyme
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rhyme
<hw>Rhyme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>ryme</ets>,
<ets>rime</ets>, AS. <ets>r⟦imac⟧m</ets> number; akin to OHG.
<ets>r⟦imac⟧m</ets> number, succession, series, G. <ets>reim</ets>
rhyme. The modern sense is due to the influence of F. <ets>rime</ets>,
which is of German origin, and originally the same word.]</ety>
<altsp>[The Old English spelling <asp>rime</asp> is becoming again
common. See Note under <er>Prime</er>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
expression of thought in numbers, measure, or verse; a composition in
verse; a rhymed tale; poetry; harmony of language.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Railing
<xex>rhymes</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>ryme</qex> I learned long ago.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He knew⟦br⟧
Himself to sing, and build the lofty <qex>rime</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>Correspondence of sound in the
terminating words or syllables of two or more verses, one succeeding
another immediately or at no great distance. The words or syllables so
used must not begin with the same consonant, or if one begins with a
vowel the other must begin with a consonant. The vowel sounds and
accents must be the same, as also the sounds of the final consonants if
there be any.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For <qex>rhyme</qex> with reason may dispense,⟦br⟧
And sound has right to govern sense.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Verses, usually two, having this correspondence with
each other; a couplet; a poem containing rhymes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A word answering in sound to another word.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Female rhyme</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Female</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Male rhyme</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Male</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Rhyme or reason</b></col>, <cd>sound or
sense.</cd> -- <col><b>Rhyme royal</b></col> <fld>(Pros.)</fld>, <cd>a
stanza of seven decasyllabic verses, of which the first and third, the
second, fourth, and fifth, and the sixth and seventh
rhyme.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rhyme</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rhyme
<hw>Rhyme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Rhymed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rhyming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>rimen</ets>,
<ets>rymen</ets>, AS. <ets>r⟦imac⟧man</ets> to count: cf. F.
<ets>rimer</ets> to rhyme. See <er>Rhyme</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make rhymes, or verses.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou shalt no
longer <xex>ryme</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There marched the bard and blockhead, side by side,⟦br⟧
Who <qex>rhymed</qex> for hire, and patronized for pride.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To accord in rhyme or sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And, if they <qex>rhymed</qex> and rattled, all was well.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rhyme</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rhyme
<hw>Rhyme</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put into
rhyme.</def> <rj><au>Sir T. Wilson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To influence by rhyme.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hearken to a verser, who may chance⟦br⟧
<qex>Rhyme</qex> thee to good.</q> <rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rhymeless</ent>⟦br⟧
